Configuring ESP8266 for VLAN 100 with DHCP (Range 1-160)

To configure an ESP8266 to operate on VLAN 100 with DHCP addresses in the range 1-160, you'll need to follow these steps. Note that the ESP8266 itself doesn't natively support VLAN tagging, but you can configure it to work on a specific VLAN by connecting it to a properly configured switch port.

Option 1: Connecting to a VLAN-configured network port

Configure your network switch port:

Set the switch port to VLAN 100 as access/untagged

Or configure it as a trunk port with VLAN 100 as native VLAN

